    Embracing the Brand Narrative of Kashmir

    ​

     

    You might have encountered a common mindset among many Kashmiri offshore businesses, including here in USA - the relentless pursuit of eliminating competition. We have seen businesses fiercely guard their secrets, strategies, and market shares.  Most entrepreneurs in the business here sought to establish monopolies in their respective domains for their individual benefits that never trickle down to Kashmir with a positive and long-lasting impact. We envisioned DE KOSHUR CRAFTS as a bridge between the artistic brilliance of Kashmiri artisans and the US market. We believe in fostering a sense of togetherness, collaboration, empowerment, and develop Kashmir Handicraft Brand. We knew that back in Kashmir, many artisans were struggling to make ends meet, their skills undervalued in a rapidly changing world. We created a platform where every skilled hand from Kashmir can find recognition and livelihood. 

     

    DE KOSHUR CRAFTS didn't just outreached Kashmiri handicrafts. We actively sought opportunities to collaborate with businesses in the USA.  DKC's mission-driven approach has paid off in ways, we could have never imagined. Let's break the mold of cutthroat competition and invite others to join us on this journey. We raised $1.3 million as business capital for the upliftment of Kashmir art and craft. This significant milestone meant more than just funds; it symbolized hope, dedication, and the power of community. The small community of Kashmiri immigrants in the U.S. had shown that even from thousands of miles away, they could make a profound impact on the lives of their brethren in Kashmir. Amir-e-Kabir's dream needs to illuminate the path for generations to come. 

    Reigniting Amir-e-Kabir's Purpose in the Modern Era, believing in his openness and collaboration

    At De Koshur Crafts, we take immense pride in our diverse business model that spans across several domains. Our commitment to excellence and innovation has led us to have industry investors and experts with a wide array of skills, each tailored to support our various ventures.     In the heart of the United States, a group of Kashmiri immigrants living & working in California, New York and DC,  embarked on a remarkable journey, one that would forever change the landscape of craftsmanship and commerce. De Koshur Crafts, born from their visionary spirit, stands as a testament as unique dedication, innovation, and unwavering commitment towards Amir-e-Kabir RA. Together, they have cultivated a unique business model that has not only attracted investors but also accommodated experts with a diverse range of skills to support various facets of De Koshur Crafts' operations.

    Nora, a recent art and craft graduate with a fresh perspective on creativity from Pennsylvania; Susan a photo-ethnographer from North Carolina, with an eye for capturing the essence of cultures and interior design background; Josefina, an advocate for sustainable practices, with Master of Science in carbon management served California; Laura, veteran and mountaineer, and borne in craftsman’s family in Seattle, Washington State, a proud American veteran, served the country with dedication and honor, after retiring from the military, used to spend months across Kashmir’s mountain ranges and wanted to embark on a new mission; Kyra, DC based, African American with a degree in applied economics, brought her economic expertise and commitment to social justice on table and completing the ensemble is Corinne, seasoned fashion designer, business woman, and philanthropist developed ownership interest in De Koshur & transform their admiration into a WOMEN, MINORITY & VETERAN-OWNED offshore DKC BUSINESS.     Consumer Behavior & The Growth Of The Handmade Industry is Promising in USA

    The Journey of $0 to $3 Million 

    Our vision extends beyond commerce. We are working tirelessly to develop 'Kashmir' as a brand synonymous with quality, luxury, & authenticity, promoted by Kashmir immigrants based in United States of America. Through this, we aim to provide a platform for the artisans of Kashmir, helping them gain the recognition they deserve on a global scale & ensuring the survival & thriving of these ancient art forms. Our endeavor is to avoid global middleman's and strong scientific advocacy against counterfeit. 

    Art and craft have been integral to human culture for centuries, embodying creativity, tradition, and cultural heritage. However, in today's globalized world, the authenticity and integrity of these creations face a growing threat from counterfeiting. To combat this challenge, we are mapping first "Brand of Handicraft Business Segment in North America" using world class technological & scientific support, including authentication techniques, forensic analysis, nanotechnology, blockchain technology, QR codes & NFC tags, digital watermarking and artificial Intelligence (AI), to be incorporated in the Art and Craft of Kashmir's Handicraft that we will  be dealing in collaboration with International AntiCounterfeiting Coalition as a powerful ally in preserving the essence of art and craft. Counterfeiting poses a significant threat to art and craft industries in Kashmir. It involves the production of imitation products that mimic the original, often with the intent to deceive consumers or gain undue financial advantage. We are determined to trickle down Science & Quality-Based Craft Education and Business Processes in Kashmir Handicraft Industry, more specifically, developments in 3d setting interactive approaches and high-end generative AI-based minimalist marketing tools, integrated online and offline marketing efforts with focus on social listening, animation marketing, geo-fencing at a various level of end-users across USA. We are clear in our Perception of Research and Development in Handicraft Industry segment improving standard of Supply and support process, global environmental compliance and regulations. 

    Craft is a skilled activity in which makers plan production, explore materials, and produce functional objects which inherit and embrace cultural meaning. Craft produces physical objects which are impossible to touch online. Augmented Reality is our offer. digital platforms provide opportunities through the 4th industrial revolution, a digital revolution characterized by a ‘fusion of technologies blurring the lines between the physical, digital and biological spheres. In Kashmir, handicrafts have to moved from ‘nostalgia’ to ‘daily life’.
